    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="letter">
                <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_NLS_42180_1840_11_13_page01.jpg"/>
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        <date when="1840-11-13">Nov. 13<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> 1840</date></dateline>
                    <salute><choice><orig>D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi></orig><reg>Dear</reg></choice> Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    The lady who will probably<lb/>
                    present this note to you<lb/>
                    is <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MoorL1">Mrs. Moore</persName>, the widow<lb/>
                    of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MoorG1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. G Moore</persName> of <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Moore-Hall_IE"><choice><orig>Moore-Hall</orig><reg>Moore Hall</reg></choice></placeName><lb/>
                   (<placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Mayo_IE">County of Mayo</placeName>, <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#IE">Ireland</placeName>)<lb/>
                    - Perhaps <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MoorG1">Mr. Moore's</persName><lb/>
                    name may be known to<lb/>
                    you, and may meet with<lb/>
                    more consideration from<lb/>
                    you as having been the<lb/>
                    friend of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#McInJ1">Sir James <unclear><choice><orig>M<hi rend="superscript">c.</hi>In=<lb/>
                    Tosh</orig><reg>McIntosh</reg><reg>Mackintosh</reg></choice></unclear></persName> than as having been<lb/>
                    a <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Mayo_IE">Mayo</placeName> Squire of great estate<lb/>
                    -(See - extract from the Diary<lb/>
                    of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MoorG1">G Moore</persName> <choice><orig>Esq<hi rend="superscript">re</hi></orig><reg>Esquire</reg></choice> in<lb/>
                    <persName ref="./Personography.xml#McInJ1">M<hi rend="superscript">c</hi>.Intosh's</persName> <title ref="./Workography.xml#Memoi12">Memoirs</title> -<lb/>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MoorG1">M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. George Moore</persName> may<lb/>
                    be <add>known</add>, - or ought to be known to<lb/>
                    you as an author - author<lb/>
                    of the <title ref="./Workography.xml#Lives1">Lives of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#WillJ1">Ripperda</persName>, - of<lb/>
                    <persName ref="./Personography.xml#JoseS1">Pombal</persName> &amp; of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#AlbeG1">Alberoni</persName></title> - <del>also</del><lb/>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_NLS_42180_1840_11_13_page02.jpg"/>
                    He had been for some years<lb/>
                    previous to his death engaged<lb/>
                    in writing a history of the French<lb/>
                    Revolution - I have never seen<lb/>
                    the manuscript, but judging<lb/>
                    from his previous works <hi rend="underline">and</hi><lb/>
                    from his conversation <hi rend="underline">and</hi><lb/>
                    the <choice><orig>correspondance</orig><reg>correspondence</reg></choice> abroad<lb/>
                    <hi rend="underline">and</hi> sources of information<lb/>
                    which I know he possessed <hi rend="underline">amp;</hi><lb/>
                    an excellent library (though in<lb/>
                    the <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Mayo_IE">County of Mayo</placeName>) I can ven<lb/>
                    ture without fear of lowering<lb/>
                    my own credit, or endangering<lb/>
                    your interest to recommend<lb/>
                    it to you receive the work of<lb/>
                    his which will be offered to you<lb/>
                    - at all events to give it your<lb/>
                    consideration. <add>Whether it be finished or<lb/>
                    a fragment I know not<lb/>
                    all this for <choice><orig>y<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>.</orig><reg>your</reg></choice> examination</add><lb/>
                    <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MoorL1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Moore</persName>, <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MoorG1">the <choice><orig>authors</orig><reg>author's</reg></choice></persName> widow<lb/>
                    the person who wishes to speak<lb/>
                    to you and to hear you speak<lb/>
                    about it is a very clever woman<lb/>
                    but not a literary lady, <del>though</del><lb/>
                    and all unused to any<lb/>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_NLS_42180_1840_11_13_page03.jpg"/>
                    <del>understan</del> business of this sort<del></del><lb/>
                    She has two sons who are<lb/>
                    literary and scientific -<lb/>
                    = <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MoorG2">The eldest</persName> a traveller, brought<lb/>
                    back levels of the <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Dead-Sea_JR"><choice><orig>dead sea</orig><reg>Dead Sea</reg></choice></placeName><lb/>
                    which I hear have raised him<lb/>
                    in public opinion - for so much -<lb/>
                    - <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MoorA1">The other son</persName> is I know<lb/>
                    distinguished at <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#University-of-Cambridge_ENK">Cambridge</placeName><lb/>
                    and in the opinion of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HamiW2">Sir<lb/>
                    William <choice><orig>Hamelton</orig><reg>Hamilton</reg></choice></persName> as one<lb/>
                    of the first mathematicians of<lb/>
                    <hi rend="underline">his age</hi> - All which I mention<lb/>
                    to you to shew you that these<lb/>
                    <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MoorX3">Moores</persName> are <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MoorX3">Moores</persName> of talent<lb/>
                    - The sons are not in <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#ENK">England</placeName><lb/>
                    at present - or probably they<lb/>
                    would have waited upon<lb/>
                    you - The manuscript was<lb/>
                    I believe left to the <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MoorL1">widow</persName>, <unclear>with</unclear><lb/>
                    injunctions to publish it: &amp;<lb/>
                    to what publisher can she be<lb/>
                    recommended with so much<lb/>
                    expectation of doing credit to<lb/>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_NLS_42180_1840_11_13_page04.jpg"/>
                    her <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MoorG1"><choice><orig>husbands</orig><reg>husband's</reg></choice></persName> literary reputation<lb/>
                    and with a certainty of being <add><unclear>so</unclear></add><lb/>
                    handsomely treated as to<lb/>
                    him to whom I have the honor<lb/>
                    and do her the favor to <choice><orig>intro-<lb/>
                    duce</orig><reg>introduce</reg></choice> her<lb/>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    I am Dear Sir<lb/>
                    Yours sincerely<lb/>
                    <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria Edgeworth</persName><lb/>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
